    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It sounds like you're feeling a deep sense of detachment, perhaps even a form of dissociation, where the connection to your surroundings and your past relationships feels severed. When you're in a space filled with strangers, it's easy to feel like an observer rather than a participant, which can amplify the feeling of being a \"glitch\" or a non-entity.\n\nHowever, the idea that the world would keep spinning exactly the same way if you vanished is a common thought during periods of depression or burnout, but it often overlooks the subtle impact you actually have on your own life and the people around you. Even if it feels like no one notices, your internal experience is real, and your presence is part of the fabric of your own reality.\n\nWould you like to talk about what's been happening back home, or perhaps explore why these cafes feel so empty to you? Sometimes just putting those feelings into words can help make them feel a bit less like a permanent state.",
